                                <div class="section-title">
                                    <h2>Recent selected publications</h2>
                                </div>

                                <p align="justify">
                                    <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2112.02034"><b>Could AI Democratise Education?
                                            Socio-Technical Imaginaries of an EdTech Revolution</b></a>, NeurIPS
                                    workshop on "Machine Learning for
                                    the
                                    Developing
                                    World", 2021.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary: In this work we ask what would it take (from a
                                    socio-technical standpoint) for a
                                    EdTech
                                    revolution to provide egalitarian and empowering access to education,
                                    beyond any political, cultural, language, geographical and learning ability
                                    barriers.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>



                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-25257-4"><b>Seasonal
                                        Arctic
                                        Sea Ice
                                        Forecasting with Probabilistic Deep Learning</b></a>,
                                Nature Communications, 2021.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary: Anthropogenic warming has led to an unprecedented year-round reduction in
                                    Arctic sea ice. This has far-reaching
                                    consequences for indigenous and local communities, polar ecosystems, and global
                                    climate,
                                    motivating the need for
                                    accurate seasonal sea ice forecasts. In this work we
                                    present a probabilistic deep learning sea ice forecasting system.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>

                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.03408"><b>Watch Less and
                                        Uncover More: Could Navigation Tools Help Users Search and Explore
                                        Videos?</b></a>,
                                ACM SIGIR Conference on Human Information Interaction and Retrieval, 2022.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary:
                                    This paper describes a novel user interface tool (the Content Flow Bar) at the
                                    intersection of AI and HCI, designed to allow users to quickly identify
                                    relevant fragments within informational videos to facilitate browsing, through a
                                    cognitively augmented form of
                                    navigation. We conducted a user study to evaluate how the tool changes the users
                                    search experience in video retrieval, as well as
                                    how it supports exploration and information seeking.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>


                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2111.07737.pdf"><b>Progress in Self-Certified Neural
                                        Networks</b></a>,
                                NeurIPS workshop on "Bayesian Deep Learning", 2021.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary:
                                    An empirical analysis of the progress towards self-certified neural
                                    networks (where predictors are trained on all the available data
                                    and certified via a
                                    generalisation bound). With this approach we do not need held-out sets for
                                    certifying the performance of the
                                    predictor or hyperparameter tuning. We
                                    show that, at least in the small data
                                    regime, self-certified learning can be claimed to have been achieved! This is an
                                    important step towards statistically sound risk certificates of
                                    performance which do not suffer from sampling bias, having potential for
                                    governing machine learning algorithms' performance.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>

                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://jmlr.org/papers/v22/20-879.html"><b>Tighter Risk
                                        Certificates for
                                        Neural Networks</b></a>,
                                Journal of Machine Learning Research, 2021.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary:
                                    This paper presents an empirical study regarding training probabilistic neural
                                    networks using training objectives
                                    derived from PAC-Bayes generalisation bounds. Our experiments
                                    show that our training methods
                                    produce very tight risk, showing promise not only to guide the learning algorithm
                                    through
                                    bounding the risk but also for model
                                    selection.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>

                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://ojs.aaai.org/index.php/AAAI/article/view/5395"><b>TrueLearn: A Family
                                        of Bayesian
                                        Algorithms to Match Lifelong Learners to Open Educational Resources
                                    </b></a>,
                                AAAI, 2020.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary:
                                    In a nutshell, the first transparent and human-centred educational recommender for
                                    educational
                                    materials!
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>


                                <p align="justify"></p>
                                <a href="https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/8818316"><b>From pairwise
                                        comparisons and rating to a unified quality scale</b></a>,
                                IEEE Transactions on Image Processing, 2019.
                                <blockquote style="font-size:15px">

                                    Summary:
                                    The goal of psychometric scaling is the quantification of perceptual experiences,
                                    understanding the relationship between
                                    an external stimulus, the internal representation and the response.
                                    We propose a probabilistic framework
                                    to fuse the outcome of different psychophysical experimental protocols, namely
                                    rating and pairwise comparisons. Such a method can be used for merging
                                    datasets of subjective
                                    nature and for experiments in which
                                    both measurements are collected. This is a stepping stone for computational social
                                    choice.
                                </blockquote>
                                </p>


